Public procurement of construction works and prevention of corruption
Joint report of the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
The awarding of services by contracting authorities is of great importance both to the State and to the economy.
The state has the task of using the public funds as economically and economically as possible and ensuring fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important element in the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure a largely unlimited competition, even cross-border, contracting authorities have to comply with EU requirements when granting contracts above certain thresholds.
To this end, the EU member states have to transpose the EU public procurement law into national law and apply it.
This has already happened both in the Czech Republic and in Germany.
Below EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate public procurement themselves.
The award of services is also a corruption-prone area.
Because of the generally high level of damage potential, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue preferential treatment when awarding their contracts.
The Supreme Control Agency of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed in January 2011 to conduct parallel audits both for the EU-wide awarding of construction services and for the prevention of corruption.
The focus of the audits was the application of the EU procurement law, which had been transposed into national regulations, as well as the prevention of corruption in the award of construction works in building construction and in road construction or transport infrastructure.
Subcontracting below EU thresholds was also included in the analysis for corruption prevention purposes.
The audit results of both SAIs are summarized in this Joint Report.
The report should also be sent to international institutions, such as To the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
Examination areas and audited bodies The Federal Court of Auditors' evaluations of the listed topics are predominantly based on cross-sectional audits carried out in 2011/2012 by the building authorities responsible for road construction and building construction in Germany.
He tested z. As the construction of highways and large building projects.
In addition, the Federal Court of Audit used results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction work in road construction, railway construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
The public procurement of the federal government in Germany is predominantly carried out by the building administrations of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Construction Administration is centrally responsible for the awarding of transport infrastructure.
In building construction, awards are made decentrally by those who use state resources.
In both countries, self-employed persons are also involved in sub-sectors of the procurement procedure.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in public procurement law and in the market structure for construction work of both countries must be taken into account.
Structure of the procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Contracting procedures limited to the national area are governed by the budgetary law and the administrative provisions based thereon.
For both EU-wide and national awards, many complementary individual rules are set by administrative rules,
such as the so-called "procurement manuals" of the Federal Government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in compliance with procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Public Procurement Act and the other legal provisions applicable both to the range above and below the EU thresholds.
Public procurement law was significantly amended in 2012.
The new regulation increased transparency in the use of public funds, facilitated increased competition and limited opportunities for corruption in the award procedure.
Principles of procurement law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the restricted procedure and the negotiated procedure are to be applied in the case of EU-wide awards.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold apply the national contracting procedures (public tender, restricted tender, free-for-sale), which, however, largely correspond to the above-mentioned EU-wide awarding procedures.
The public procurement law in Germany is characterized by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (assignments to be carried out throughout the EU) and the public invitation to tender (by national awards).
Any interested company may submit an offer in the open procedure and in the public invitation to tender.
Another key feature of German procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized companies.
Above all, the division of a total construction measure into specialized and partial lots serves this purpose.
The individual awarding of these lots should enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above features of German procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.
In Germany, more than 330,000 construction companies employ 1.9 million people.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable to construction projects below the EU threshold.
An exception to this is the simplified procedure, where below the thresholds and under certain conditions a less stringent procedure may be applied.
The Czech public procurement law contains provisions, in accordance with EU law, that contracts should be concluded when competition is ensured and a favorable price is achieved.
The current legislation in the Czech Republic allows contracting entities to choose between the open and the non-open procedure.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 are companies with 20 or more employees.
