Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel tests in their countries for the EU-wide awarding of construction works and for preventing corruption.
The working groups of both SAIs compared the relevant legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, in particular in the fields of building construction and road construction.
In essence, they stated:
The EU directives on the award of works by contracting authorities have been transposed into national law both in the Czech Republic and in Germany (points 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, the prevention of corruption is also governed by the procurement regulations of both countries, which differ in some aspects in their focus and detail (Section 3.2).
In both countries, a key requirement of the tender documents is that they must contain all the information needed for proper tendering.
The specifications must be neutral and must not be restrictive to competition.
In Germany, the tender documents have largely met these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it continues to be a problem to sufficiently define the subject of the contract.
In Germany, construction work should be divided into lots, if possible, in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.
In its inspections, especially in the field of road construction, the NKÚ stated that the awarding of extensive services without lots or with very large lots could affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.
Constraints on market potential can result in significant cost increases and involve the risk of price or other collusion.
Under the terms of both countries, contracting entities may, under certain conditions, in principle, agree additional or changed services with the contracting companies which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (point 4.1).
The respective specifications for determining the type of award were largely followed in both countries.
Under the rules of the Czech Republic, contracting entities may freely choose between open and restricted procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary priority of the open procedure for EU-wide awards and the public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national awards, applies.
This allows more companies to submit offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, makes price fixing between bidders difficult and leads to the most economical results.
In the case of construction projects whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited construction authorities generally awarded the construction services throughout Europe.
The correct estimation of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of award.
In Germany, cost databases are used for costing public buildings, especially in building construction,
which are based on the evaluations completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in road construction, but it is not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).
In the case of works to be awarded throughout Europe, prior information and announcements must be published. This is intended to strengthen competition by allowing interested companies to prepare for the planned awards at an early stage.
The audited building authorities usually followed this requirement.
In some cases, misstatements, incorrect applications or lack of controls may affect competition (point 4.3).
The selection of applicants for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to tampering.
Under EU law, the number of invited candidates must be high enough to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, not discriminate and be announced in advance.
In addition to EU requirements, contracting entities in both countries are to switch as often as possible among applicants in the selection of candidates.
In order to counteract the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed specifications in Germany.
The audited administrations did not take into account these requirements in some cases.
In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (paragraph 4.4).
In both countries, in the bidding phase, in order to ensure fair competition, it is important to ensure that companies interested in receiving tenders receive the same information.
Contact between these companies with each other and with freelancers involved in drawing up the terms of reference must be avoided as far as possible in order to avoid anti-competitive agreements.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
The audited building authorities in Germany partially did not comply with these requirements (No. 4.5).
When opening up tenders, in both countries particular attention must be paid to the MehrAugen principle and the principle of transparency.
The requirements for labeling, documentation, custody and confidentiality of the offers should restrict the scope for manipulation and are particularly well defined in Germany.
The tests in both countries showed few complaints (No 4.6).
Examination and evaluation of the offers are defined in both countries by specifications for the structure and process organization.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but were not consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.
Contracting authorities, for example, handed over quotes to third parties for examination without having to go through the offers beforehand and adequately document irregularities.
The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).
When concluding the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition will be informed about the intended contract prior to the award of the contract.
This legal protection option also has a preventive function against corrupt behavior.
The Czech Republic also provides for judicial review of non-EU procurement procedures.
Only in a few cases did contracting authorities not comply with the deadlines set by the contract or did they deviate from the bidders' offer (point 4.8).
The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible for the audited building authorities in both countries.
The EU-wide transparency requirement was not adequately implemented in the award notes of some of the proceedings.
Also, some of the identified deficiencies mitigated the corruption prevention function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries largely fulfilled their reporting and reporting obligations (point 4.9).
Fundamentals of EU procurement law and corruption prevention
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union for the free movement of goods and services, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted inter alia the Procurement Coordination and Remedies Directives, which were to be transposed by the Member States into national law.
The general principles of the award of the European Union are, in particular, the requirement of competition, the requirement of equal treatment or non-discrimination, and the requirement of transparency.
In order to achieve these objectives, the Procurement Coordination Directive lays down specific rules for works contracts to be awarded throughout the EU for construction projects.
For this purpose, their prospective order totals must reach or exceed a current level of 5,000,000 euros.
In particular, the rules concern the content of the tender documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of time limits, including the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of the candidates and The Remedies Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.
In the event of possible infringements of public procurement law, the companies concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed by means of review procedures.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.
corruption prevention
Importance of corruption prevention
In both countries there is no legal definition of the term corruption.
In general, corruption is understood as the misuse of a trust to a private advantage,
usually caused by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause considerable economic damage.
It is estimated that the worldwide cost of corruption is 5% of world economic output.
For the European Union, the scale of these costs is estimated at 1%.
For contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may call into question trust in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of contracting authorities.
In doing so, they have to check the organizational structure and procedures of their administrations for areas that are particularly susceptible to corruption in order to take appropriate precautionary measures against corruption.
Preventive action and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making to corruption.
The award of public works is generally considered to be a particularly vulnerable area of corruption.
Measures to prevent corruption
In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery as well as acceptance and approval of benefits - is prosecuted under penal and employment law.
In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a guideline and recommendations on corruption prevention in the federal administration. Accordingly, the following principles must be observed in addition to the risk analysis for the awarding area: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multiple eyes principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, awarding and billing, precise and complete documentation of the award procedures.
In addition, other anti-corruption provisions have been included in the procurement regulations.
For example, in 2011 the responsible Federal Ministry for Contracts for Federal Highway Systems introduced an electronically-based control system,
with the award data - such. For example, the estimated costs and the contract sums - as well as information on the freelancers involved are collected across the board and analyzed for abnormalities.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labor law.
The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of tenderers as well as the prohibition of any discrimination are the most important bases of corruption prevention.
For public procurement, the Czech Government has set out anti-corruption measures in an anti-corruption strategy paper for 2011-2012 and updated them for 2013-2014.
Some of the measures recommended therein have already been transposed into national public procurement law and related administrative provisions14.
The new legislation essentially contains the following provisions: reduction of thresholds for smaller contracts, obligation to prior notice of contract awards by the contracting authority, including the grounds for invitations to tender, prohibition of restricting the number of tenderers in restricted procedures and thus abolishing bidder selection options Lottery procedure, introduction of the obligation to publish the procurement documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Examination results on the individual phases of the award procedure
Vergabeunterlagen
Tender documents The tender documents must contain all the information that the tenderers need for a proper tender.
In particular, the tender documents must enable an accurate calculation.
In doing so, the bidders must not be assigned any risks that can not be calculated on their part.
The tender documents consist in particular of the terms of reference and the terms of contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that determine the selection of the most economical bid.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
The requirements of EU law for the tender documents are in particular related to the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and are intended to restrict competition as little as possible.
The service description must always be product-neutral.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the specification is only permitted under strict conditions.
The avoidance of restrictive rules in the tender documents is also an elementary principle of corruption prevention.
In addition, unclear or inaccurate information in the tender documents should be avoided, since they open up scope for speculation in the preparation of tenders and manipulation in their valuation.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules In both countries, the EU legal requirements for technical specifications have been transposed into national law.
The services are basically product-neutral without requiring specifications.
In the service descriptions, the individual services usually have to be subdivided in detail into service units with respective quantities.
Here, prices are to be agreed on the basis of service units (eg Euro per m² or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases may services be defined by functional targets.
The specifications must in any case be complete and clear.
They must contain exact quantities and must not include services for which it is not certain that they will be needed.
Remunerations after lump sums or after time expenditure are to be avoided as far as possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indeterminate requirements in the tender documents.
The specifications must enable tenderers to submit their tenders safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The invitation to tender should only be made public when the tender documents have been completed.
Divergent regulations
An obligation to tender for works in lots does not exist in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible to decide on the type of service to be commissioned, the public contracting authorities may subdivide construction work into several lots.
In Germany construction work is always divided into lots, separated according to the quantity (partial lots) and / or according to type or subject areas (professional lots).
This should enable medium-sized companies to participate in the competition, expand the number of potential suppliers and make price-fixing more difficult.
This type of award is considered the most economical as a rule.
Scoring criteria in the Czech Republic must be indicated in the tender documents for both EU-wide and national procedures.
This should make it completely and conclusively clear to the applicants which criteria their offers are to be evaluated.
In Germany, the specification of evaluation criteria in EU-wide announcements, but no later than in the tender documents, is only required for EU-wide procurement procedures.
In national procurement procedures, the scoring criteria are to be recorded only in an internal administrative award.
Tender documents drawn up by commissioned freelancers may not contain any references to these offices or participating planners or appraisers in Germany in the structural engineering and in some road construction administrations.
This is to prevent individual companies from obtaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages through contact with these freelancers without the knowledge of the client.
This is also the reason why freelance contractors can neither send nor submit planning documents for inspection.
The contact person of the companies is the client alone.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.
Additional or changed services that prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements) are almost always the case for large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions allow, to some extent, the granting of addenda to the contractor without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary services may not exceed half of the main order.
In addition, the additional services must not be allowed to separate from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a threshold of 20% applies to such award without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of a delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the ongoing construction work.
If supplementary services are also transferred to the company already commissioned, the contractor will not be able to arbitrarily increase the prices for these services in accordance with the regulations in Germany.
When determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for the price determination of the order already placed must be assumed.
In addition to supplementary services, it may also lead to a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, small quantities can not be offset against additional supplements.
Essential test results
BHR
Technical specifications and product-neutral tender
In individual cases, the terms of reference contained references to national technical approvals or standards which had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.
Some specifications also contained product-related requirements - such as for graffiti protection, waterstops or noise barriers - without this being necessary.
In some cases, performance requirements were described so precisely that only one product was eligible.
Bills of services subdivided by sub-services
BRH has not found in any of the audited procedures violations of the obligation to tender services in principle in a list of services subdivided into partial services.
Completeness of the service descriptions
In the vast majority of procedures, the tender documents were completed before the tenders were launched.
For some procedures, the tender documents had to be corrected during the bid phase as some positions or deadlines had changed.
Occasionally, the bills of ladders contained positions where it was not clear whether they were needed.
Almost half of a bill of quantities for demolition work consisted of such demand positions.
Lots and scoring criteria
For many awards lacked the mandatory justification, why the mostly out of tenders advertised services were not further divided into parts.
There were no complaints when specifying the criteria that are to be used in the evaluation of the offers.
Notes on Freelance Workers
A small part of the specifications contained references to the freelancers involved.
Their names were in part on the cover pages or in attached plans or reports.
In one case, the contracting authority even explicitly requested candidates to contact the architect "on questions of tenders".
In particular in the field of building construction, the contracting authorities attributed the alleged complaints mainly to negligence on the part of the freelance contractors responsible for drawing up the specifications.
The construction services pointed to the lack of capacity to adequately control the specifications.
SAO
Technical specifications and product neutral tendering In the public procurement for the construction of a dwelling house with 12 housing units, a supplier and a specific product brand were specified in the service description.
The contracting authority did not allow the use of comparable products without giving reasons.
In the construction of several university buildings, suppliers and products were also specified in the invitation to tender.
Service descriptions with performance units
For construction projects in some industrial areas, the awarding authority did not clearly state the scope and nature of the required services in the specifications.
As power units, it merely indicated the enclosed space of the individual buildings in cubic meters.
Completeness of the service descriptions
In the construction of a motorway bypass, the specifications were changed four times in the framework of a restricted procedure from August to September 2009,
as the scope of supply had increased significantly and the technical requirements had changed.
Contract documents for social housing included inaccurate location information, inadequate preliminary civil engineering studies and incomplete design drawings, which required additional services.
When constructing a large library building, the specification of the interior design contained no product quality requirements.
As a result of these missing requirements, some subcontractors built overpriced and inappropriately high-quality equipment.
Lots and eligibility criteria
In the Czech Republic, the division of construction work into partial lots or the assignment of partial orders is not mandatory.
An examination of the three major sections of the construction of a motorway ring showed that, with a selective allocation of selected parts, savings of up to EUR 31.6 million with a total cost of EUR 620.3 million would have been possible.
For example, in the case of six different works, which were the subject of a single contract, it would have been possible to save 2.5 million (25%) on a single lot.
If the construction of 20 bridges had been awarded in bulk, savings of EUR 11.5 million (25%) would have been possible compared to a total allocation.
When awarding construction works in road construction, the central contracting authority made very extensive reference requirements as suitability criteria.
In the construction of part of a motorway, the contracting authority requested from the tenderers, in an open procedure, inter alia, the proof of at least three road projects completed, worth EUR 28 million in each of the past five years.
In the Czech Republic at most nine suppliers met these requirements.
The public award of a different section of a motorway included six separate construction projects in which the contracting authority had set an annual construction volume of at least € 480 million over the last three years as a suitability criterion for the companies.
Two-thirds of the funds invested in road construction projects in 2008 and 2009 (ie € 2.5 billion out of a total of € 3.7 billion) came from a total of five companies that carried out the work alone or as a consortium.
In 46 procurement procedures with a contract volume of € 528 million, only two or even one bidder submitted an offer.
The NKÚ pointed out that narrowing the market potential can result in significant cost increases.
Additional services
In the construction of an autobahn bypass, the contracting authority did not apply any of the statutory procedures when awarding additional services in two cases and did not conclude any written contracts for the additional services.
Due to unclear volume and quality requirements, supplements in the first case of up to € 63.7 million (net) and in the second case up to € 165.4 million (net), resulting in a respective order volume of 21% and 91, respectively % increased.
