Further findings
On the basis of a sampling of construction projects, NKÚ found that the average cost of building a four-lane motorway kilometer in the Czech Republic is up to € 14.6 million.
In Germany, according to an evaluation of long-term data of the Federal Ministry of Construction, the average cost of a four-lane motorway kilometer is up to 10.4 million euros.
This comparison indicates that highway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary findings
The basic rules on the procurement documents are largely consistent in both countries and take into account the EU rules.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and corruption prevention.
For example, the requirement for sufficient certainty in the specifications should enable bidders to reasonably calculate and prepare their tenders,
protect the client against additional services to be agreed later and also limit speculative margins.
The common basic requirements for the procurement documents are supplemented in Germany by regulations that are intended to further reduce competitive restrictions and manipulation options.
In the Czech Republic, there are no such targets, but transparency is increased by publishing the evaluation criteria in non-EU-wide procurement procedures.
The requirements for the specification of services have largely been complied with in both countries.
In some cases, however, it was necessary to object to deviations which may have led to restrictions of competition.
The existing requirement in Germany for the formation of lots promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the audit findings of the NKÚ, the award of comprehensive services without lots or with only very large lots can lead to restrictions of the provider field to only a few large companies.
Comprehensive reference requirements in road construction in the Czech Republic have led to public contracts being awarded only to a small number of suppliers and smaller and medium-sized enterprises not being able to compete.
Also, a limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increase the risk of price or other collusion.
When allocating and compensating for additional or changed benefits, the regulatory approaches in both countries differ.
According to the EU requirements as well as the German regulations supplementary performance with a value up to half of the main order can under certain conditions be awarded without public procurement procedure.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20% up to which additional benefits may be awarded by negotiated procedure without notice to the original contractor.
