because the scope of services for public contracts is often poorly defined.
If the excess is greater than 20%, the additional services must be put out to public tender.
By splitting benefits into lots, restrictions on competition and resulting adverse consequences can be avoided.
Define the type of procurement and take into account the EU threshold
By determining the type of award, the contracting authority determines the scope of the number of companies participating in the competition.
It can leave the circle of potential candidates and tenderers largely unlimited, for example by choosing an open procedure, or limit it by specifying non-public procurement procedures.
For construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, pan-European procurement procedures shall apply.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
In choosing the type of award, the contracting authority must take into account in particular the European competition law requirements and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of a construction project is at or above the EU threshold of currently € 5,000,000, the construction work can generally be awarded across Europe in open or restricted procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiated procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
The contracting authority may, to a limited extent, deviate from the principle of pan-European procurement and award construction work in national procurement procedures, provided that the estimated value of the contract is less than EUR 1,000,000 and the sum this lot does not exceed 20% of the estimated total value of all works contracts.
A uniform construction project may not be divided into individual measures without compelling reason or deliberately estimated at too low cost values, in order to avoid the obligation to award the building services in principle throughout Europe.
Since restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the type of award is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed justification of the chosen type of procurement as well as the examination of the obligation to apply the EU public procurement rules are important components of the documentation of the award procedure.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar regulations
Both countries have fully transposed the EU legal requirements on procurement procedures and the threshold into national law.
Divergent regulations
The Czech Republic has also transferred the principle equality of open and restricted procedures contained in the EU Directive to its works contracts, which are not subject to EU rules.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the non-open procedure, without the need to document or justify the decision. Other methods, however, are possible only under certain conditions defined by law.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or - in the case of national awards - the public invitation to tender have priority. This is determined by the budgetary and public procurement law as well as by the guidelines for the prevention of corruption.
Other types of procurement - as well as the non-open procedure or the restricted invitation to tender - are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated in public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be reasonably substantiated and documented.
The principle of the primacy of the open procedure or public invitation to tender is intended to ensure that competition is as unrestricted as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by specifying certain tenderers and to impede possible price fixing among tenderers.
The principle of public tendering is a central element of corruption prevention in Germany.
The correct estimation of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of award.
The construction services in Germany can use the planning and cost databases of public administrations and other organizations to determine the probable costs in the field of public building construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost characteristics for building categories, units of use, building elements or individual building services.
On the basis of such cost parameters, the prospective order value of a planned project or of a construction work to be awarded can be determined.
Corresponding cost databases for the road construction in Germany have only a few building administrations.
A nationwide introduction for all road construction administrations is planned.
Contracting entities in the Czech Republic can not rely on central databases or average price estimates for comparable construction works in determining the likely cost of construction works.
On the contrary, the cost estimates are in most cases based on estimates of the financing body or on the amount of funds made available to the construction service.
Measures for the standardization of costing procedures are still in their infancy.
The relevant ministries received the mandate under the Anti-Corruption Plan for 2011-2012 to create a database of standardized building materials and materials.
