Selection of candidates for non-public procurement
In contrast to public procurement procedures, in the case of non-public procurement procedures, it is not possible for every undertaking interested in the performance of the services to be awarded to participate in the competition.
In the case of non-public procurement procedures, the contracting authority must make a selection in advance of which companies should be invited to submit tenders.
Requirements of EU Law and Preventing Corruption The EU rules allow a limitation of the number of applicants in the EU-wide non-public procurement procedures.
However, in restricted procedures, at least five companies must be invited to submit tenders.
At least three companies should be invited for negotiated procurement procedures.
In any case, the number of invited candidates must be high enough to ensure real competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not lead to discrimination and must be announced in advance.
The selection of companies to be solicited is a process within the procurement process which is highly vulnerable to manipulation, e.g. B. in this case certain companies can be unilaterally preferred.
In addition, restricting competition to a few companies also favors possible agreements between the applicants.
In both cases, the delivery result may be significantly affected at the expense of the client.
The contracting entities must therefore take special precautions against possible manipulation, carry out adequate checks and in particular ensure the transparency and traceability of this procedural step.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar regulations
The rules for selecting candidates are similar in both countries.
