Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
EU regulations provide for a multi-stage procedure:
First of all, the suitability of the tenderers has to be determined.
Tenderers must be economically and financially sound and have the required professional and technical expertise.
In principle, companies are to be excluded from participation in the award procedure. B. are legally convicted of bribery or fraud.
The offers of the non-excluded bidders shall be calculated, technically and economically evaluated and assessed on the basis of the previously announced award criteria.
The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer. The client has to check special offers with unusually low prices.
The review and evaluation of bids is a particularly susceptible to manipulation phase of the procurement process.
For example, bidders may be unjustifiably excluded or bids that do not meet the requirements may be left in competition.
By favoring or discriminating against bidders, the result of the evaluation may be unduly impaired and thus the determination of the most economically advantageous offer can be prevented.
The contracting entity must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons responsible for the audit and the evaluation meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It also has to ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure as well as the decisions taken.
