There were two cases of irregularities in one of the audited building authorities, both of which were reported to the technical supervision level.
In one of the cases, the tendering procedure for two bidders was identical so that the contracting authority excluded both tenders from the procedure.
In the application of the remaining provisions, the tests did not reveal any significant complaints.
SAO
Qualifying Examination
For many of the projects under construction, including university construction, road construction and rail network development, contracting entities did not exclude tenderers from the procedure, although they did not meet the requirements set out in the tender documents or could not demonstrate their suitability to the extent required. On the other hand, in one case, a contracting entity could neither substantiate nor explain why it had excluded a tenderer who had met the requirements.
rating
When awarding works for a water treatment plant, the contracting authority did not take account of the criteria for the assessment and evaluation of tenders.
In a construction project for the expansion of the rail network, the awarding authority determined the weighting of the evaluation criteria only at the beginning of the scoring.
In the case of road maintenance measures, the given criterion "shortening of the construction phase" was wrongly assessed in a procedure.
As a result, the offered reductions were insufficiently taken into account for the second and third tier bidders.
Documentation of the offer selection
In the case of three contract award procedures, the contracting authority did not document the criteria used and on what basis it had selected the successful tenderer.
When contracting a freeway, the contracting authority selected companies for smaller orders of up to € 20,000 solely on the basis of telephone surveys at prices and delivery conditions.
Examinations of this selection were not possible because the interviews were not documented.
Summary findings
The regulations for checking and rating the offers in both countries comply with EU regulations.
However, in the case of details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective regulations differ.
In Germany, the procedure is regulated more precisely by detailed requirements, in particular with regard to the implementation of the multiple-eye principle and the protection of offers than in the Czech Republic.
The same applies to the specifications on the basis of which the appropriateness of the offered prices is to be examined.
In both countries, it had to be found in some of the audited procurement procedures that essential procedural steps in the review and evaluation of bids were not documented or insufficiently documented.
Without traceability and transparency of audit and valuation decisions, however, possible manipulative interventions are favored.
A particularly serious defect was the transfer of all offers to third parties, without the contracting authority having sufficiently examined and documented the offers and thus protected them against possible manipulation in the further proceedings.
If contracting authorities allow tasks to be carried out by third parties during the examination and evaluation of bids, sufficient precautions and increased control effort are required to counteract the increased risk of manipulation.
When examining the appropriateness of prices, the audited departments in Germany did not always make full use of the set of instruments and did not adequately examine the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, complaints arose mainly in the aptitude test and in the application of the scoring criteria.
Completion of the award procedure
After examining and valuing the tenders, the award procedure is concluded by awarding the contract or by canceling the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the planned award decision.
Companies have the possibility to examine the intended award by electronic means or by fax within 10 days, or by other means of communication within 15 days, and if necessary initiate a review procedure.
Before expiry of this period, a contract may not be concluded.
