In the case of a construction measure in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the offer of the bidder in the contract.
For some contracts, such as road construction maintenance, highway construction and a bypass, the contracting entities concluded the contracts after the legal deadline.
When awarding construction works for the rehabilitation of former military premises, the contracting authority did not forward the notice of contract award to all tenderers until after expiry of the statutory period.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the EU's requirements for completing the procurement procedure.
The legal protection of unsuccessful candidates or tenderers will increase the scope for preventing corruption.
The scope of legal protection in the Czech public procurement law has also extended to awards below the EU thresholds.
In both countries, the deadlines for placing an order were exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
The building authorities should avoid the identified deficiencies in concluding their procurement procedures in the future.
Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations
The award procedures must be documented comprehensibly during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings and the reasons for the individual decisions.
In the case of EU-wide procedures, the orders placed must be announced.
The order data are also recorded in an EU statistics.
Requirements of EU Law and Preventing Corruption The documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.
Careful and timely documentation first makes traceability of the award decisions possible.
In particular, it also serves the effective legal protection of tenderers in the case of contract awards above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential element in preventing corruption, as the need to justify award decisions greatly limits the scope for manipulation.
The contract award notice for an EU-wide procurement procedure shall be sent by the respective contracting entity to the EU's Publications Office within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU, thereby also implementing the principle of transparency.
In addition, the contracting entities must collect the essential data from their procurement procedures and report them to the EU Commission through the relevant national ministries.
On this basis, the EU Commission annually compiles EU statistics, which enable it to gain an overview of the development of the internal market in construction works.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar regulations
Both countries have fully transposed the EU legal requirements for documentation and reporting obligations into national law.
The documentation and reporting rules for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Divergent regulations
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to disclose issued contracts is not limited to EU-wide awards but also covers the other procurement procedures.
The notice period is shortened to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide awards, publication is only required for restricted tenders and for free-handed assignments of more than € 25,000 or € 15,000 excluding VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these limits, as well as in public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition proceedings will receive information on the awarding of orders.
