Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two key issues which are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of works by contracting authorities: the application of EU public procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The provisions of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Corruption prevention measures not only serve to prevent or at least reduce corruption. They should also avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two SAIs on the application of public procurement rules in both countries, and the comparison of these rules, provide insight into similarities and differences that may help both countries to develop their procurement legislation and to apply it.
Application of the EU public procurement rules
The EU's specifications for the award of construction works have been transposed into national law by both countries.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common ground for the awarding of works and consideration of the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the undertakings involved and transparency of procurement procedures.
The building administrations of both countries have in some cases very extensively reduced these bids through further administrative regulations.
The Czech Republic has to a large extent also transferred the requirements for EU construction works to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the audit offices have shown that the building authorities did not fully comply with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The building authorities in Germany should further improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to be able to remedy the reported complaints when implementing the EU regulations.
Above all, the audits in the Czech Republic have identified dangers that affect the profitability of the contracts.
For example, incomplete service descriptions made additional services necessary, which were often awarded in breach of legislation. In addition, the cost estimates were usually insufficiently prepared. Excessive skill requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, especially for transport structures.
corruption prevention
The investigations did not aim to expose cases of corruption,
also because the SAIs do not have the necessary tools for this.
However, the SAIs can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken action against corruption and manipulation in the awarding of works and how these requirements are applied.
In preventing corruption, both countries have set different priorities.
Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition and transparency and controls as central elements of corruption prevention.
The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction work and tailored to their specific needs.
The relevant regulations sometimes specify very precisely how the precautionary measures must be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In the opinion of the BRH, in particular, the primacy of the open procedure or public tender procedure is an appropriate instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the award of construction works. Restrictions on competition increase the risk of manipulative interference.
Risk analysis and sufficient controls (especially the multi-eye principle), transparency requirements and documentation of procurement procedures as well as various organizational measures are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.
Therefore, the BRH does not see any fundamental need for amendment of the corresponding requirements of the administrations in the awarding of construction services.
The rules for the prevention of corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in some areas have revealed shortcomings in the implementation of some requirements.
The building authorities should further train their employees on the guidelines for corruption prevention and raise their awareness of this issue even more.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks delegated by the building authorities to the self-employed.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, delegating tasks increases the risk of abuse.
Tampering and corruption-prone tasks should therefore only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can thereby ensure a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interventions.
SAO
At the governmental level, the Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption, in which public procurement is the most important element.
The Public Procurement Act and the associated implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The tests of the NKÚ took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The adopted strategy and new legislation are likely to be effective improvement measures as contracting entities justify the economics of order placement, the calculation of expected prices, the adequacy of qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the assessments and duly document and publish all these aspects have to.
recommendations
The NKÚ and the BRH generally rate the implementation of EU regulations as positive.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's rules of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of works within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also be used as a basis for similar projects to enable and promote cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and non-material damage potential through manipulation and corruption in the awarding of construction services, both courts of audit see the construction authorities in their countries called upon to continue their measures against corruption and manipulation and to improve them if necessary.
In particular, the organization and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously analyzed for vulnerabilities and risks in order to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures can provide wider scope for competition and significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
In addition, a greater division of construction into lots may have a favorable effect on bid prices, provided that this increases competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient public procurement by contracting authorities.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialized building authorities. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, these tasks - with the exception of transport projects - are carried out by the ministries themselves or contractors appointed by them.
The audit offices of both countries have the desire, even after completion of their joint project, to further develop the insights that are important to them and, if necessary, to pass them on to the parliament and government of their country.
Both SAIs are also convinced that the principles of procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are of international interest to the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI). For the principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to counteract corruption effectively and to guarantee the economic award of construction works in a well-functioning and fair competition.
